<div class="info-box">
  <h3>Before we start the exercises...</h3>
  <p>There's a new problem to solve for all this stay and release based training: Up until now we've only been marking short, momentary behaviors like eye contact, getting onto the platform, or sitting. But now we need markers for <em>sustained</em> behaviors too. Here's how we break it down.</p>
</div>

<h2 class="learn-heading">Learn: Two New Markers üìö</h2>

<p>There's a new problem to solve for all this stay and release based training. Up until now all of our markers break up, as our current marker ("yes") is what's called a <strong>terminal marker</strong> and it ends the behavior.</p>

<p class="my-4"><span class="marker-green">Your "Terminal Marker":</span> Your current marker ("yes"). It means "You did it! üéâ Get up." This is our standard marker we conditioned back in Lesson 1. The terminal marker basically finishes the job for the exercise.</p>

<p class="my-4"><span class="marker-yellow">Your "Continuation Marker":</span> A new marker. I recommend a tonally neutral "good." The marker means <strong>stay right there</strong>. This is our sustained behavior marker. It tells the dog you're on the right track, keep doing what you're doing.</p>

<div class="warning-box">
  <h3>‚ö†Ô∏è Your "Feedback Marker"</h3>
  <p>The feedback marker is <strong>optional</strong>. A verbal, tonally neutral correction. A quick "nope" or "uh-uh" that serves as corrective feedback. It communicates to the dog that what they're doing is not what we want. <strong>Do not use "no" as a correction marker</strong> because many people use it emotionally and will end up scaring or confusing their dog with its variable use. Don't worry, a well-timed correction marker is mild. Think of it like a buzzer on a gameshow.</p>
</div>

