<h2 class="learn-heading">Learn: Marker Usage and Release for a Sustained Behavior</h2>

<p>Most of the things we ask our dogs to do in sustained behavior. Here's how the 3 markers are used in tandem:</p>

<ol class="list-decimal list-inside my-4 space-y-2">
  <li>Give the command (e.g. "place")</li>
  <li>‚úÖ <strong>Use continuation marker ("good")</strong> to tell them to stay and deliver a reward.</li>
  <li>Wait a few seconds to let them build up their patience.</li>
  <li>‚ö†Ô∏è If they break the stay, use the feedback marker ("nope"). Gently guide them back into the position.</li>
  <li>‚úÖ Use the continuation marker ("good") and reward when they return to the right position.</li>
  <li>üéâ <strong>Release with "free"</strong> and celebrate!</li>
</ol>

<p class="my-4" style="clear: both;">When "Place" is first learned, it's a 5-10 second stay. 30 seconds is great. Don't get frustrated if your dog gets off. They're just learning. It's like learning patience. This is a marathon, not a sprint.</p>

<div class="exercise-section">
  <h3>Exercise: "Place" with the Implied Stay</h3>

  <p>Now that you've got the tool kit of markers, let's start building duration on "place." Use what you learned above about markers to guide them through longer and longer stays.</p>

  <ol>
    <li><strong>Send your dog</strong> to "place".</li>
    <li>If they're on the platform, use the continuation marker <strong>"good"</strong> and reward while they're still on it. This tells them to stay put.</li>
    <li>After 5-10 seconds, release with <strong>"free"</strong>.</li>
    <li>Gradually increase the time before releasing.</li>
  </ol>
</div>

<div class="tips-box">
  <h3>Tips and Tricks</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>‚òùÔ∏è Build duration slowly. Going from 10 seconds to 60 seconds takes weeks, not days.</li>
    <li>‚òùÔ∏è If your dog breaks the stay repeatedly, you've increased duration too quickly.</li>
    <li>‚òùÔ∏è Mark and reward multiple times during longer stays.</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<div class="exercise-section">
  <h3>Exercise: "Sit" and "Down" with the Implied Stay</h3>

  <p>The exact same process applies to "sit" and "down." Each command implies "hold this position until I say free." Use your continuation marker to reward patience and your release word to end the exercise.</p>
</div>

<h2 class="learn-heading">Increasing the Difficulty</h2>

<p>Once your dog understands the implied stay for "place," it's time to start increasing the difficulty with the 3 Ds:</p>

<p class="my-3"><strong>Duration:</strong><br>Slowly increase how long they stay. If your dog breaks, that's just information. Your dog is at its limit in that particular environment. Track durations so you can see improvements. Try to increase 10 to 15 seconds. Then increase. "3 to 5 then 5 to 10, etc."</p>

<p class="my-3"><strong>Distraction:</strong><br>Once you're confident in the staying and in the timing, change the environment or something like ping something. Track durations so you can see improvements and trends over time.</p>

<p class="my-3"><strong>Distance:</strong><br>Get an "Implied Stay" for 15 seconds. Then 30 seconds. Then increase. "Place to Place 15. to Place 30."</p>

